<p><i><b>Hyperion</b></i> is a <a href="/wiki/Hugo_Award" title="Hugo Award">Hugo Award</a>-winning 1989 <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a> novel by <a href="/wiki/Dan_Simmons" title="Dan Simmons">Dan Simmons</a>. It is the first book of his <a href="/wiki/Hyperion_Cantos" title="Hyperion Cantos">Hyperion Cantos</a>, and is the only book in it to extensively employ the literary device of the <a href="/wiki/Frame_story" title="Frame story">frame story</a> (although arguably <i><a href="/wiki/The_Fall_of_Hyperion" title="The Fall of Hyperion">The Fall of Hyperion</a></i> also uses it, but to a lesser extent). The plot of the novel is highly complex, featuring multiple <a href="/wiki/Worldline" title="Worldline" class="mw-redirect">time-lines</a> and characters whose behavior changes dramatically.</p>
